        <name>7.3.4.2 Exercise 2 (NOT IN QUIZ)</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Using any of the properties of determinants to minimise the arithmetic, evaluate the determinants of the following matrices:
\[A = {@matrixa@}, \qquad B={@matrixb@}\]
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;

&lt;li&gt;
&lt;div&gt;\(\det(A)=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;div&gt;\(\det(B)=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use Property 4 to take out common factors in the rows and the columns of \(A\):
\[\det(A)=720\det{@reducedAA@}\]
Note that the first entry in column 3 is a \(1\). This is very useful: use Property 5 to simplify the matrix by adding/subtracting an appropriate multiple of column 3 from columns 1 and 2:
\[\det(A)=720\det{@veryreducedAA@}\]
The value of this determinant is most easily found by expanding along the top row. Since two of the entries are \(0\) and the third is \(1\), and the sign associated to the \(1\) is \(+\), the value is just the determinant of \({@relevantminor@}\), which is {@DD@}.&lt;p&gt;Therefore the determinant of \(A\) is \({@DD@}\cdot720={@ta1@}.\)
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;The determinant of \(B\) is \(0\) because row 4 is \(2\) times row 1.&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
